e processes of decolonisation and neoliberalism unfolded.This book traces how successive Labour and Conservative governments have incrementally dismantled the democratic settlement. A bipartisan commitment to neoliberalism has culminated in a historic crisis of representation and legitimacy, opening the door to competing nationalist forces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracyzGreat BritainxHistory. 4amanchesterhive variable pricing textbooks. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aAnti-racism.  aBritish Empire.  aBritish democracy.  aNew Labour.  aScottish Independence.  aThatcherism.  anationalism.  aracism.  aworking-class.1 aMcGeever, Brendan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcGeever, Brendan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVirdee, Satnam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2023 eBook-Packagez9783111206455oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616460540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526164605423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526164605/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2023